WEBVTT

00:06.006 --> 00:07.216
(knock on door)

00:07.258 --> 00:09.218
Hello?

00:09.260 --> 00:11.846
(indistinct chatter over radio)

00:11.887 --> 00:13.472
Hello?

00:13.514 --> 00:15.975
Oh, boy.

00:16.016 --> 00:18.227
-You remember me?
-Oh, yeah.

00:18.269 --> 00:20.354
-Long time no see.
-Oh, yes.

00:20.396 --> 00:23.733
Well, I've been very busy.
Traveling.

00:23.774 --> 00:27.361
-You want a slice?
-Oh, no, thank you.

00:27.403 --> 00:28.738
I was just in the neighborhood,

00:28.779 --> 00:30.948
and I thought I would drop in
and say hello.

00:30.990 --> 00:32.992
-To me.
-Yes.

00:37.538 --> 00:40.750
-Hello.
-Hello.

00:40.791 --> 00:43.002
Anything else?

00:43.043 --> 00:45.004
No.

00:45.045 --> 00:47.006
Oh, well, as long as I'm here,

00:47.047 --> 00:50.009
Miriam-- my daughter, remember?

00:50.050 --> 00:54.054
Well, her husband left her,
and she's been living with us,

00:54.096 --> 00:56.182
and recently I found out
that she's...

00:56.223 --> 00:58.184
Aren't you gonna make some tea?

00:58.225 --> 01:00.102
-I don't like tea.
-(chuckles):
The tea isn't for you.

01:00.144 --> 01:01.604
It's for me. I drink it,

01:01.645 --> 01:03.773
-and you read the leaves.
-Don't need it.

01:03.814 --> 01:07.234
Oh, you use the ball, right.
Or cards?

01:07.276 --> 01:09.612
Oh, no, I remember.
You like fire.

01:09.653 --> 01:12.156
Just sit there.

01:12.198 --> 01:14.200
Let me look at you.

01:22.792 --> 01:25.169
Okay. What do you want to know?

01:25.211 --> 01:26.837
Um, well, my d-daughter...

01:26.879 --> 01:28.380
-Miriam.
-Why, yes.

01:28.422 --> 01:30.341
You just told me her name.
Don't get too impressed.

01:30.382 --> 01:34.970
Yes, uh, well, she's, um,
pursuing a career in...

01:35.012 --> 01:37.389
comedy,

01:37.431 --> 01:39.058
which is bad enough in itself,

01:39.099 --> 01:41.811
but there's a very viable man
in the picture now,

01:41.852 --> 01:44.814
and I am so worried that this...

01:44.855 --> 01:48.275
career will be the downfall
of this relationship.

01:48.317 --> 01:49.860
Tell me, what do you see?

01:49.902 --> 01:51.904
Hmm.

01:54.281 --> 01:58.661
I see a perky brunette
with a signature hairstyle.

01:58.702 --> 02:00.830
Oh, that's her. That's Miriam.

02:00.871 --> 02:02.498
She's standing
in front of a big crowd.

02:02.540 --> 02:04.083
A wedding? That's a wedding.

02:04.124 --> 02:06.377
She's the object
of deep adoration.

02:06.418 --> 02:08.546
That's Benjamin.
He'll adore her.

02:08.587 --> 02:10.631
H-He'll be weirdly subtle
about it

02:10.673 --> 02:12.383
and do it in
a slightly robotic way, but...

02:12.424 --> 02:14.468
I see her talking.

02:14.510 --> 02:17.721
Speaking very quickly
into a microphone.

02:17.763 --> 02:19.557
That's her speech. She gave
a speech at her first wedding,

02:19.598 --> 02:21.517
and she's doing it again.
Oh, I'm so...

02:21.559 --> 02:23.185
Does she mention shrimp?

02:23.227 --> 02:24.770
-What?
-Never mind. Who cares?

02:24.812 --> 02:26.772
She's getting married.
Oh, I'm so glad

02:26.814 --> 02:29.692
I just happened to be strolling
by here with no intention

02:29.733 --> 02:31.652
of coming in at all,
and then I did. Oh, here.

02:32.695 --> 02:34.822
Thank you.

02:34.864 --> 02:38.117
Thank you so much.
I'll see you next week.

02:38.158 --> 02:41.453
There's gonna be a wedding.

02:41.495 --> 02:43.455
(chuckles)

02:44.498 --> 02:46.250
I don't know why you'd wear

02:46.292 --> 02:50.170
a black cocktail dress
to a wedding, but...

02:50.212 --> 02:52.214
whatever.

02:55.050 --> 02:58.012
(announcer shouting over radio)

02:58.053 --> 03:00.347
-What time is it?
-Early. 9:00, 10:00.

03:00.389 --> 03:03.475
-12:30. I should go.
-Really? You bored?

03:03.517 --> 03:05.394
I'm supposed to be
in my dorm room by midnight.

03:05.436 --> 03:07.396
This is the third time this week
I've missed curfew.

03:07.438 --> 03:09.106
Third time this week
I'll have to climb in my window

03:09.148 --> 03:11.191
-to avoid getting caught.
-I thought your curfew was 1:00.

03:11.233 --> 03:12.985
-You did not.
-Yeah.

03:13.027 --> 03:15.112
I just like watching you climb
in that window.

03:15.154 --> 03:17.740
Hey, we saw them tonight.
We saw you tonight.

03:17.781 --> 03:19.033
-Oh, yeah?
-Mm-hmm.

03:19.074 --> 03:20.200
-Good or bad?
-Great.

03:20.242 --> 03:21.577
Especially the last number.

03:21.619 --> 03:23.370
Told you we needed
that last number.

03:23.412 --> 03:25.998
-You're impossible.
-Impossible and right.

03:26.040 --> 03:27.750
-We should go.
-You know, I'm tired

03:27.791 --> 03:29.335
of having to take you home
at night.

03:29.376 --> 03:31.337
-I can just grab a cab, then.
-Not what I meant.

03:31.378 --> 03:34.173
-Horse and buggy? Magic carpet?
-Don't go back to your dorm.

03:34.214 --> 03:36.383
-Where am I supposed to go?
-My dorm.

03:36.425 --> 03:39.053
Oh, now, Mr. Maisel,
you know good girls

03:39.094 --> 03:41.013
don't stay out all night
with their gentlemen callers.

03:41.055 --> 03:43.265
I mean, what would
the neighbors think?

03:43.307 --> 03:44.975
That you're a dime-store floozy?

03:45.017 --> 03:46.894
Dime-store? In these shoes?

03:46.936 --> 03:50.230
Well, if you won't let me
sully your reputation,

03:50.272 --> 03:53.108
then I guess I'll just have to
make an honest woman out of you.

03:53.150 --> 03:55.444
♪ We go along
harmonizing a song ♪

03:55.486 --> 03:57.571
-What's this?
-A Cadillac.

03:57.613 --> 03:59.114
♪ Or I'm reciting a poem ♪

03:59.156 --> 04:01.951
Well, then, I'm definitely
gonna have to learn to drive.

04:01.992 --> 04:04.161
-You like it?
-I love it.

04:04.203 --> 04:06.121
I just didn't think
this would happen so fast.

04:06.163 --> 04:07.498
Oh, but you knew
this would happen?

04:07.539 --> 04:09.208
Well, yeah. I mean, come on.

04:09.249 --> 04:11.335
Hey, what did my father say
when you asked him?

04:11.377 --> 04:13.003
Oh, shit.
I was supposed to do that?

04:13.045 --> 04:15.297
-Joel.
-Forget him.

04:15.339 --> 04:18.217
What do you say? Yes? Great.

04:18.258 --> 04:20.386
I say I need to think about it.

04:20.427 --> 04:23.138
What? No. There's the ring.
Let's go.

04:23.180 --> 04:26.016
-It's just so sudden.
-You knew this was gonna happen.

04:26.058 --> 04:27.309
I knew this was gonna happen.

04:27.351 --> 04:29.103
Well, then,
you know your answer.

04:29.144 --> 04:32.022
-Uh...
-If you don't say yes right now,

04:32.064 --> 04:33.732
I'm gonna walk out
in the middle of the street

04:33.774 --> 04:35.234
and wait for a bus
to run me over.

04:35.275 --> 04:36.819
Pay the bill first?

04:36.860 --> 04:39.279
Okay.

04:39.321 --> 04:41.907
-Here I go.
-(door opens, closes)

04:41.949 --> 04:43.617
♪ Talking my baby ♪

04:43.659 --> 04:45.619
♪ Loving my baby ♪

04:45.661 --> 04:47.454
♪ I don't mean maybe... ♪

04:47.496 --> 04:48.914
(horns honking)

04:48.956 --> 04:51.333
That man is crazy.

04:51.375 --> 04:54.253
Yeah, he certainly is.

04:54.294 --> 04:55.796
MAN:
Get out of the road, asshole.

04:55.838 --> 04:57.172
-Come on!
-(tires squealing)

04:57.214 --> 04:59.967
-Say yes.
-No.
-MAN: Move!

05:00.009 --> 05:02.344
-Move, you idiot!
-Not moving.

05:02.386 --> 05:05.681
I'm concerned our children might
come out clinically insane.

05:05.723 --> 05:08.350
Very good chance. Say yes.

05:08.392 --> 05:10.269
Maybe.

05:10.310 --> 05:11.395
MAN: Get the fuck out
of the road, pal.

05:11.437 --> 05:12.688
MAN 2:
Come on, I got to get home.

05:12.730 --> 05:14.356
♪ Are in each other's arms ♪

05:14.398 --> 05:17.693
Oh, no. Not fair.

05:17.735 --> 05:19.111
-Fuck fair!
-MAN: Come on.

05:19.153 --> 05:20.696
My favorite show.

05:20.738 --> 05:22.990
-He took me three times.
-(women chuckle)

05:23.032 --> 05:24.825
I'm going for broke,
Miriam Weissman.

05:24.867 --> 05:28.162
♪ Shall we dance? ♪

05:28.203 --> 05:30.080
You have to say yes first.

05:30.122 --> 05:31.373
♪ On a bright cloud of music ♪

05:31.415 --> 05:33.917
Fine. Yes.

05:33.959 --> 05:36.670
-Yes! (giggles)
-(honking continues)

05:36.712 --> 05:39.048
You have to put the ring on.

05:39.089 --> 05:42.092
-Exhausting.
-JOEL: Put it on.

05:42.134 --> 05:43.969
MAN:
Come on, move it, buddy.

05:44.011 --> 05:47.306
♪ When the last little star
has left the sky ♪

05:47.347 --> 05:49.516
♪ Shall we still be together ♪

05:49.558 --> 05:51.727
♪ With our arms
around each other ♪

05:51.769 --> 05:55.105
♪ And shall you
be my new romance ♪

05:55.147 --> 05:56.356
(crowd cheers)

05:56.398 --> 05:58.484
♪ On the clear understanding ♪

05:58.525 --> 06:00.402
♪ That this kind of thing
can happen ♪

06:00.444 --> 06:01.862
♪ Shall we dance? ♪

06:01.904 --> 06:04.907
Now, this next part's
gonna go very badly.

06:07.409 --> 06:09.411
(crowd cheering)

06:13.123 --> 06:15.125
(applause)

06:27.930 --> 06:29.932
(Benjamin speaking softly
nearby)

06:36.480 --> 06:38.857
BENJAMIN: Mark Greenwald
is the president of the bank

06:38.899 --> 06:41.485
and an old family friend in case
you want to give him a call.

06:41.527 --> 06:44.530
Right here, these are
last year's financials,

06:44.571 --> 06:46.073
tax returns, bank statements.

06:46.115 --> 06:47.783
As you can see,
I can clearly provide for her.

06:47.825 --> 06:49.660
Anything she needs,
anything the children need,

06:49.701 --> 06:51.370
they will be very comfortable.

06:51.411 --> 06:55.082
So you want to marry
my daughter.

06:55.124 --> 06:57.376
With your permission, yes, I do.

06:57.417 --> 07:00.838
-And you've spent time
with Miriam.
-I have.

07:00.879 --> 07:03.215
-So you understand Miriam.
-I do.

07:03.257 --> 07:05.342
Could you explain her to me?

07:05.384 --> 07:08.262
-That was a joke, Benjamin.
-Right, sorry.

07:08.303 --> 07:10.973
Humor is very important
in our house, Benjamin.

07:11.014 --> 07:13.142
-Of course.
-If you are going
to marry Miriam,

07:13.183 --> 07:14.852
-you will have to learn that.
-I understand.

07:14.893 --> 07:16.520
Because to Miriam,
almost everything in the world

07:16.562 --> 07:19.690
is a joke. I had to stop
watching the news with her.

07:19.731 --> 07:21.441
Guggenheim,
the name of the museum,

07:21.483 --> 07:24.486
-caused 20 minutes
of uncontrolled giggling.
-(laughs)

07:24.528 --> 07:27.698
Why? Who knows.
That's just Miriam.

07:27.739 --> 07:28.949
I will learn to laugh, sir.

07:28.991 --> 07:30.951
You're going to need
a lot of closet space.

07:30.993 --> 07:33.495
-I have seen the hats.
-There will be
a lot of activity.

07:33.537 --> 07:35.122
Things will shift quickly.

07:35.164 --> 07:38.167
Your reality,
your vacation plans.

07:38.208 --> 07:40.127
And God knows what
those children will be like

07:40.169 --> 07:42.045
when they grow up.
I cannot vouch for them.

07:42.087 --> 07:44.131
I will not hold you responsible.

07:44.173 --> 07:46.341
It's awfully quick,
your courtship.

07:46.383 --> 07:48.927
Anything I should know that will
certainly kill her mother?

07:48.969 --> 07:51.430
No. I've just waited a long time
to find the right person,

07:51.471 --> 07:53.015
and now I have. That's all.

07:53.056 --> 07:57.102
ABE: Well, if this
is truly your intention,

07:57.144 --> 07:59.104
in addition to the bank records,

07:59.146 --> 08:03.025
I will need
25 character references.

08:03.066 --> 08:04.902
Are you going to
write this down?

08:04.943 --> 08:06.361
There's a list.
I'll need to know

08:06.403 --> 08:08.447
the names and birth dates
of your family,

08:08.488 --> 08:11.408
how religious you are,
what your hobbies are,

08:11.450 --> 08:14.703
what percentage of time
you spend on such hobbies,

08:14.745 --> 08:16.705
are you a dog or a cat man--

08:16.747 --> 08:19.583
very important--
your favorite authors.

08:19.625 --> 08:22.628
You see, Benjamin,
after the Joel fiasco,

08:22.669 --> 08:24.046
I am taking this decision

08:24.087 --> 08:25.672
very, very seriously.

08:26.715 --> 08:29.426
You have somewhere else to be?

08:29.468 --> 08:32.012
No. Well, surgery.

08:32.054 --> 08:34.139
But never mind. Go on.

08:34.181 --> 08:36.225
I'll need to know
all political affiliations,

08:36.266 --> 08:37.476
favorite baseball team,

08:37.517 --> 08:38.977
favorite radio shows...

08:39.019 --> 08:41.146
Mr. Weissman,
could you excuse me a minute?

08:41.188 --> 08:42.981
I need to use the bathroom.

08:43.023 --> 08:46.443
Oh. That's something you do?

08:46.485 --> 08:48.487
Yes.

08:48.528 --> 08:50.530
All right. If you must.

08:55.160 --> 08:57.162
Oh.

08:59.164 --> 09:01.500
-What was that for?
-I just needed to make sure

09:01.541 --> 09:03.377
-you're worth all this.
-I am.

09:03.418 --> 09:05.420
God, this is much harder
than I thought it was gonna be.

09:05.462 --> 09:07.714
My father's a complicated man.
But once this is over,

09:07.756 --> 09:09.091
you guys are going to be
very close.

09:09.132 --> 09:11.134
-It will never be over.
-It will be.

09:11.176 --> 09:12.970
Four patients have already died
this morning.

09:13.011 --> 09:15.514
-A small price to pay.
-I thought
we were making progress

09:15.555 --> 09:17.140
when we stumbled
onto the Big Bang theory.

09:17.182 --> 09:19.184
How do you stumble
onto the Big Bang theory?

09:19.226 --> 09:21.186
And then he asked
if I snack in between meals.

09:21.228 --> 09:22.854
-You said no, right?
-I said it depends.

09:22.896 --> 09:25.107
-Oh, dear.
-It does. It's snacking.

09:25.148 --> 09:26.858
There's no plan.
That's what makes it snacking.

09:26.900 --> 09:29.444
Okay, relax. You're doing fine.
And get back in there.

09:29.486 --> 09:31.071
If he thinks you're taking
too long in the bathroom,

09:31.113 --> 09:32.406
there will be
a very thorough physical

09:32.447 --> 09:34.449
-in your future.
-Bye.

09:36.159 --> 09:38.120
Is this how you look
in the morning?

09:38.161 --> 09:39.705
Yes, it is.

09:39.746 --> 09:42.124
I'll never make it
to work on time again.

09:42.165 --> 09:44.251
-I'm back.
-ABE:
That was quick. Good for you.

09:44.293 --> 09:46.211
Get these downstairs
to accounting now

09:46.253 --> 09:48.005
-or no one gets paid.
-ALL: What?!

09:48.046 --> 09:50.257
Everyone's getting paid!
It's an expression.

09:50.299 --> 09:52.884
-Get back to work.
-Mr. Maisel, phone.

09:52.926 --> 09:54.511
The Dutch fabric shipment's
gone missing.

09:54.553 --> 09:56.263
How does a truckload of fabric
go missing?

09:56.305 --> 09:58.265
-Joel, are we on for tonight?
-I have the kids tonight.

09:58.307 --> 10:00.225
-I love kids.
-Great. Go have some.

10:00.267 --> 10:02.853
-Never mind, they found it.
-Where?

10:02.894 --> 10:05.105
Times Square.
The driver had an audition.

10:05.147 --> 10:07.357
Get the shipment,
fire the driver. In that order.

10:07.399 --> 10:09.026
Okay, see, when I gave you

10:09.067 --> 10:11.403
that giant amount of money
to go away,

10:11.445 --> 10:14.239
-I expected you to go away.
-I don't have time
right now, Pop.

10:14.281 --> 10:17.409
I fired you, and you responded
by bringing your children here.

10:17.451 --> 10:20.495
Is that hostile or adorable?
I just can't tell.

10:20.537 --> 10:23.081
I'll go. I'm going.
I just have to figure out where.

10:23.123 --> 10:24.583
In the meantime, Mrs. Moskowitz,

10:24.624 --> 10:25.959
when is the Joseph Miller
meeting again?

10:26.001 --> 10:27.544
-4:45.
-4:45?

10:27.586 --> 10:29.171
That's what he said, 4:45.

10:29.212 --> 10:31.089
Hey, what are you drawing there,
Ethan?

10:31.131 --> 10:33.258
Mommy's friend. Bathroom!

10:33.300 --> 10:36.386
Mr. Maisel, I am not cleaning
that bathroom again.

10:36.428 --> 10:38.138
I got it, Mrs. Moskowitz.

10:38.180 --> 10:40.807
He's like a sprung garden hose,
that child.

10:40.849 --> 10:42.893
-Mommy's got a friend.
-Fuck you.

10:42.934 --> 10:45.771
Aha, baby's first swear word.

10:45.812 --> 10:47.939
Definitely not her first.

10:49.983 --> 10:52.652
What is your life, anyhow?

10:52.694 --> 10:55.113
JOEL:
Ethan!

10:55.155 --> 10:57.449
Remember, pal, you have to look
where you're aiming

10:57.491 --> 10:59.326
-when you use the urinal.
-Why?

10:59.368 --> 11:02.204
Because if you keep hitting
the floor and the counter

11:02.245 --> 11:05.040
and the ceiling,
no girl's ever gonna marry you,

11:05.082 --> 11:06.625
and Mrs. Moskowitz
is gonna leave your daddy,

11:06.666 --> 11:08.168
so we'll both be alone.

11:08.210 --> 11:11.338
Hey. So, Mommy has
a new friend, huh?

11:11.380 --> 11:13.048
-Yeah.
-And you met him?

11:13.090 --> 11:14.633
-Yeah.
-Where?

11:14.674 --> 11:15.842
At the park.

11:17.886 --> 11:19.554
I thought you had to go
to the bathroom.

11:19.596 --> 11:21.598
ETHAN:
Not fun now!

11:23.642 --> 11:26.645
-This one?
-Second wedding.

11:30.232 --> 11:33.235
-This one?
-Second wedding.

11:35.779 --> 11:37.280
-This one.
-Miriam, please.

11:37.322 --> 11:39.616
You can't wear white.
It's a second wedding.

11:39.658 --> 11:42.619
-You can wear champagne.
-I don't want to wear champagne.

11:42.661 --> 11:44.955
It's not a color. It's what
happens when white gets sad.

11:44.996 --> 11:48.083
Well, I'm sorry. Second weddings
are subtle, dignified.

11:48.125 --> 11:50.544
No big halls or lavish dinners.

11:50.585 --> 11:52.629
Second weddings mean 40 guests

11:52.671 --> 11:54.589
and a luncheon at home
with scrambled eggs.

11:54.631 --> 11:56.216
Wow.
What's the third wedding mean?

11:56.258 --> 11:57.676
Third wedding means I'm dead.

11:57.717 --> 11:59.719
-Can I wear white?
-Keep looking, please.

11:59.761 --> 12:01.513
There may not even be a wedding
at this rate.

12:01.555 --> 12:03.306
Papa still hasn't said yes.

12:03.348 --> 12:04.766
Plus, he said
if he does say yes,

12:04.808 --> 12:06.810
-he's not gonna pay for it.
-Yes, he will.

12:06.852 --> 12:09.563
He'll pay for a second wedding
here at home with scrambled...

12:09.604 --> 12:11.690
Scrambled eggs
and a champagne dress.

12:11.731 --> 12:13.442
Oh, now cheer up.
You can still give a toast.

12:13.483 --> 12:15.485
I know you have your heart set
on giving a toast.

12:15.527 --> 12:17.028
-How do you know that?
-Ladies.

12:17.070 --> 12:18.697
Papa. Hi!

12:18.738 --> 12:21.199
There's a sandwich for you
in the refrigerator, Abe.

12:21.241 --> 12:23.869
Papa? Hey, Papa?

12:23.910 --> 12:25.704
Papa? Papa?

12:25.745 --> 12:27.747
Miriam, do you get paid
by the "Papa"?

12:27.789 --> 12:29.916
-No.
-(sighs)

12:29.958 --> 12:33.003
-So, Papa...
-Pickles.

12:33.044 --> 12:35.130
I was just wondering
if you've thought any more

12:35.172 --> 12:36.673
about your talk with Benjamin?

12:36.715 --> 12:39.217
-No.
-No? Just no?

12:39.259 --> 12:41.428
No. Yes, no.

12:41.470 --> 12:44.097
Well, you know from experience,
the sooner you book a hall,

12:44.139 --> 12:45.557
the better deal you get.

12:45.599 --> 12:47.392
ROSE:
No hall! Second wedding!

12:47.434 --> 12:49.352
I do not have an answer yet.

12:49.394 --> 12:52.022
Well, is there anything
you want to talk about with me?

12:52.063 --> 12:54.232
-No.
-Anything I can tell you?

12:54.274 --> 12:56.735
-No. Wait. Yes.
-Great. What?

12:56.776 --> 12:58.737
Do you ever call him Ben?

12:58.778 --> 13:00.739
-No.
-Benny?

13:00.780 --> 13:02.824
-No.
-Dr. Ben?

13:02.866 --> 13:04.784
-No.
-Okay.

13:04.826 --> 13:06.912
Thank you for that information.

13:06.953 --> 13:09.915
Papa? Papa...

13:09.956 --> 13:12.375
For a woman who wants to make
her fortune on the stage,

13:12.417 --> 13:14.252
you have
an extremely limited vocabulary.

13:14.294 --> 13:15.837
Why won't you give
your permission?

13:15.879 --> 13:17.672
I didn't say
I wouldn't give my permission.

13:17.714 --> 13:19.341
I just said
I haven't decided yet.

13:19.382 --> 13:20.926
Well, what's taking you so long?

13:20.967 --> 13:22.886
I have to run his numbers again.

13:22.928 --> 13:24.513
I don't think
his figures add up.

13:24.554 --> 13:26.181
It's not fair to make him wait.

13:26.223 --> 13:27.891
Well, if he doesn't like it,

13:27.933 --> 13:30.310
he can go ahead and marry you
without my permission.

13:30.352 --> 13:32.062
Joel did.
That turned out great.

13:32.103 --> 13:34.606
Forget it.

13:34.648 --> 13:36.483
When I've decided, you'll know.

13:36.525 --> 13:38.527
-Fine.
-I'll send up a flare.

13:38.568 --> 13:40.570
Super.

13:40.612 --> 13:42.489
Miriam, wait.

13:42.531 --> 13:44.866
I need to ask you something.

13:47.911 --> 13:50.455
What did you say in Washington?

13:50.497 --> 13:52.582
What did I say about what?

13:52.624 --> 13:55.502
In your club date--
what did you say about...

13:55.544 --> 13:57.212
about me?

13:57.254 --> 13:59.214
Papa, I swear,
that night in the Catskills

13:59.256 --> 14:01.466
was a total
and complete anomaly.

14:01.508 --> 14:03.802
-So you didn't talk
about me at all?
-I did not.

14:03.843 --> 14:06.221
Cross my heart and swear to God
on the life of my kids.

14:06.263 --> 14:08.557
-Oh, wait.
-You did talk about me.

14:08.598 --> 14:10.350
-Just a little.
-What did you say?

14:10.392 --> 14:12.936
-It's very important
that I know.
-I said,

14:12.978 --> 14:14.563
"Is Senator Kennedy
running for president?

14:14.604 --> 14:16.523
"It's up to Jackie.
You know she wears the pants

14:16.565 --> 14:18.358
-in that family."
-No, she doesn't.

14:18.400 --> 14:19.818
Well, I haven't gotten
to the part about the linen.

14:19.859 --> 14:21.236
-What linen?
-Her pants are linen.

14:21.278 --> 14:23.113
-Who cares what fabric they are?
-No.

14:23.154 --> 14:25.657
The whole point of the bit is
she wears linen pants,

14:25.699 --> 14:27.450
and they wrinkle
while you're ironing them.

14:27.492 --> 14:30.078
You know, you don't seem to be
getting any better at this.

14:30.120 --> 14:31.871
-Let me start again.
-Please don't.

14:31.913 --> 14:33.915
Just skip to the part about me.

14:33.957 --> 14:37.377
I said, I found you listening
to my four-year-old's record,

14:37.419 --> 14:39.671
a song about teaching yourself

14:39.713 --> 14:41.840
to wipe your, uh... tushie,
after going to the bathroom,

14:41.881 --> 14:44.217
and you said you were listening
to it, because at work,

14:44.259 --> 14:46.011
you're trying
to teach a computer to sing.

14:46.052 --> 14:49.472
And what was the punch line?

14:49.514 --> 14:51.808
Now I'm wondering,
does my father not know

14:51.850 --> 14:53.810
-how to go to the bathroom?
-Okay.

14:53.852 --> 14:55.812
-And if that's true,
who taught me?
-I get it.

14:55.854 --> 14:57.772
-Because my mother never goes
to the bathroom.
-That's enough.

14:57.814 --> 14:59.566
-I heard my name!
-No, you didn't.

14:59.608 --> 15:01.860
What else did you say?
About Bell Labs?

15:01.901 --> 15:04.446
-About the work there?
-Nothing.

15:04.487 --> 15:06.698
No specifics about what I do?

15:06.740 --> 15:09.117
I don't know what you do.
I've never known what you do.

15:09.159 --> 15:11.661
Most of the time, I have no idea
what you're talking about.

15:11.703 --> 15:14.122
I have no idea why we're having
this conversation right now.

15:14.164 --> 15:16.124
All right.

15:16.166 --> 15:18.168
I believe you.

15:25.091 --> 15:27.427
We haven't finished
our Benjamin conversation yet.

15:27.469 --> 15:29.179
-Yes, we have.
-I want an answer.

15:29.220 --> 15:31.598
-Okay. No.
-You're right. Take your time.

15:33.933 --> 15:36.269
-What do you think?
-I think it's a piece of shit.

15:36.311 --> 15:38.980
That's the eighth chair
you said was a piece of shit.

15:39.022 --> 15:41.524
I believe all eight are
genuinely a piece of shit.

15:41.566 --> 15:44.277
Jackie, we can't throw out
every fucking chair.

15:44.319 --> 15:46.696
Now, just tell me, what can
you fix and what can't you fix?

15:46.738 --> 15:48.448
-Fix?
-Repair.

15:48.490 --> 15:50.325
-Me?
-Yeah, you.

15:50.367 --> 15:52.035
Who told you
I can fix anything?

15:52.077 --> 15:53.703
I thought you were a carpenter.

15:53.745 --> 15:55.413
Who the fuck told you that?

15:55.455 --> 15:57.582
Isn't that what you did
before you worked here?

15:57.624 --> 16:00.251
No! Oh, wait.

16:00.293 --> 16:03.088
Yes, I did. I am a carpenter.

16:03.129 --> 16:05.423
So can you fix these?

16:05.465 --> 16:07.217
Absolutely.

16:07.258 --> 16:08.968
(phone ringing)

16:09.010 --> 16:10.679
What?

16:10.720 --> 16:13.765
I just... Never mind.

16:17.102 --> 16:18.561
Gaslight.

16:18.603 --> 16:20.313
-WOMAN: Susie Myerson?
-Yeah?

16:20.355 --> 16:22.190
I'm calling
on behalf of Sophie Lennon.

16:22.232 --> 16:24.192
-Oh, shit.
-Excuse me?

16:24.234 --> 16:28.071
I, um... I'm bleeding.
Uh, could I call you back?

16:28.113 --> 16:29.656
Miss Lennon
requests your presence

16:29.698 --> 16:31.866
at her house this Friday,
1:00 sharp.

16:31.908 --> 16:33.326
-What? Why?
-She is requesting it.

16:33.368 --> 16:34.994
Friday, 1:00 sharp.

16:35.036 --> 16:36.746
Uh, Friday's not really good
for me.

16:36.788 --> 16:38.707
My mistake.
She is demanding your presence

16:38.748 --> 16:40.709
at her house Friday, 1:00 sharp.

16:40.750 --> 16:42.585
-But...
-215 East 98th Street.

16:42.627 --> 16:44.796
Eat before you come.
Lunch will not be served.

16:44.838 --> 16:46.172
-Wait!
-(line clicks)

16:46.214 --> 16:48.133
-(sighs)
-(dial tone)

16:48.174 --> 16:50.009
(upbeat jazz music playing)

16:50.051 --> 16:52.053
That was Sophie Lennon
summoning me to her house.

16:52.095 --> 16:54.222
Can you believe that?
After what Harry Drake did?

16:54.264 --> 16:56.391
After what she did to Midge?
Is she crazy?

16:56.433 --> 16:58.601
-You got to go.
-What do you mean, I got to go?

16:58.643 --> 17:00.395
-No way.
-You fucked up.

17:00.437 --> 17:02.522
You went off,
you made things worse.

17:02.564 --> 17:06.651
Now you got to go eat some shit
to make things right for Midge.

17:06.693 --> 17:07.902
Midge wouldn't want me
to eat shit.

17:07.944 --> 17:09.612
Doesn't matter what she wants.

17:09.654 --> 17:12.490
You're the manager. You go to do
what's best for your client.

17:12.532 --> 17:14.659
I don't like this side
of you, Jackie.

17:14.701 --> 17:17.036
-What side?
-Rational. It's freaking me out.

17:17.078 --> 17:21.166
Look, one thing I know about,
even more than carpentry,

17:21.207 --> 17:24.002
and this is
from personal experience--

17:24.043 --> 17:27.380
in life, sometimes you got
to eat a whole lot of shit.

17:27.422 --> 17:30.842
Piles of it.
More shit than you can imagine.

17:30.884 --> 17:33.970
If you took a pack of wolves
with stomach issues,

17:34.012 --> 17:36.097
and locked them
in your apartment for a month,

17:36.139 --> 17:38.016
and then came home with a spoon,

17:38.057 --> 17:40.435
that's the amount of shit
I'm talking about.

17:40.477 --> 17:42.020
Thank you for the vivid imagery.

17:42.061 --> 17:44.397
Life is basically
an all-you-can-eat shit show.

17:44.439 --> 17:46.941
-You're disgusting.
-Yup, but I'm right.

17:49.861 --> 17:53.114
Hey, I fixed it.
How the fuck do you like that?

17:53.156 --> 17:55.158
(Jackie chuckles)

17:57.076 --> 17:59.913
Joel? It's me. Can I come in?

17:59.954 --> 18:01.831
(Esther babbles)

18:01.873 --> 18:03.917
(Esther shouts)

18:03.958 --> 18:05.710
Hi. Sorry I'm late.

18:05.752 --> 18:07.086
Ethan, grab your bag.

18:07.128 --> 18:08.838
-Your mother's here.
-Everything okay?

18:08.880 --> 18:10.256
You were supposed
to be here at 6:00.

18:10.298 --> 18:11.800
I know. I'm sorry.

18:11.841 --> 18:13.468
They are both fed,
but Ethan's decided

18:13.510 --> 18:15.595
he wants an additional
bedtime meal, so you figure out

18:15.637 --> 18:18.056
what the hell that means
so I can be prepared next time.

18:18.097 --> 18:19.599
-Joel...
-Bye, pal.

18:19.641 --> 18:21.643
-See you in a few days.
-Joel, what's the matter?

18:21.684 --> 18:23.394
-Nothing.
-Why are you giving me
the brush-off?

18:23.436 --> 18:25.063
I'm not giving you
the brush-off.

18:25.104 --> 18:27.190
I have to work, you have to go.
Case closed.

18:27.232 --> 18:29.108
Okay, but...

18:29.150 --> 18:31.778
Okay, I'll drop them off
on Friday.

18:31.820 --> 18:33.822
-Yup.
-Come on.

18:35.615 --> 18:38.701
I heard about Ethan meeting
your new friend at the park.

18:38.743 --> 18:42.330
-Oh, Joel...
-You know, I have friends, too.

18:42.372 --> 18:44.916
Maybe I should introduce them
to the kids at the park.

18:44.958 --> 18:46.835
I'm sorry. It was a mistake.

18:46.876 --> 18:48.920
Mama told him we were there.
I didn't invite him.

18:48.962 --> 18:50.380
Those are my children, Midge.

18:50.421 --> 18:52.090
I have a right
to know who's meeting them.

18:52.131 --> 18:53.967
-I agree. I told him that.
-Oh, you did? When?

18:54.008 --> 18:56.386
When he showed up. I told him
that you didn't know about it,

18:56.427 --> 18:58.263
and I needed to tell you
before I introduced them.

18:58.304 --> 18:59.681
This is bullshit.

18:59.722 --> 19:02.016
-I thought we were playing nice.
-We are.

19:02.058 --> 19:03.726
My kids!

19:03.768 --> 19:05.603
Mine! I should be informed

19:05.645 --> 19:07.522
before you hand them over
to another man.

19:07.564 --> 19:09.774
I didn't hand them over
to another man.

19:09.816 --> 19:12.110
He showed up by accident.
It was not intentional.

19:12.151 --> 19:14.028
Don't make this a thing.

19:14.070 --> 19:16.364
It is a thing!
It's a big fu...

19:17.824 --> 19:19.909
I have to work.
You have to go.

19:19.951 --> 19:21.369
You're being unreasonable.

19:21.411 --> 19:23.454
Oh, am I?
Well, you should leave me then.

19:23.496 --> 19:24.873
Oh, wait.

19:24.914 --> 19:27.041
I didn't leave you. You left me!

19:27.083 --> 19:29.460
And then you left me back!
Figuratively speaking.

19:29.502 --> 19:31.337
-Bye.
-Bye!

19:35.341 --> 19:38.136
ETHAN:
We used a urinal.

19:38.177 --> 19:40.346
JOEL: She's got a friend,
a fucking...

19:40.388 --> 19:42.348
-friend!
-I hate friends.

19:42.390 --> 19:44.142
Kids have all sorts of friends.

19:44.183 --> 19:46.227
"Come meet my kids.
We're in the park."

19:46.269 --> 19:48.938
Three kids.
It's a lot of friends.

19:48.980 --> 19:50.481
They're my kids, asshole.

19:50.523 --> 19:52.025
My kids!

19:52.066 --> 19:54.152
Your two kids.
I've got three.

19:54.193 --> 19:57.280
Three kids, same income!

19:57.322 --> 19:58.907
"It was an accident."

19:58.948 --> 20:00.491
Accident, my ass.

20:00.533 --> 20:02.452
Accidents happen all the time,

20:02.493 --> 20:06.247
especially after four Rob Roys,
hence... three kids!

20:06.289 --> 20:08.458
You know what? I'm done.

20:08.499 --> 20:12.045
Me, too. I don't care
what Imogene's mother says.

20:12.086 --> 20:13.588
(grunting)

20:13.630 --> 20:16.591
I know I fucked up, okay?

20:16.633 --> 20:19.594
I fucked up! I get it!

20:19.636 --> 20:21.721
And I've been paying
for it for a year.

20:21.763 --> 20:23.348
No more.

20:23.389 --> 20:25.350
She wants to live her life?
Great.

20:25.391 --> 20:26.851
I get to live mine, too.

20:26.893 --> 20:29.395
Well, someone should,
'cause it won't be me.

20:29.437 --> 20:31.189
Three kids!

20:31.230 --> 20:33.232
My mother of all people-- she
told me to stop waiting around.

20:33.274 --> 20:35.568
Well, here you go, Ma. You win!

20:35.610 --> 20:37.278
Mothers always win.

20:37.320 --> 20:39.197
Three kids!

20:39.238 --> 20:41.407
She's not the only one
who gets a dream.

20:41.449 --> 20:43.368
I'm gonna have a dream.

20:43.409 --> 20:45.620
My dream?

20:45.662 --> 20:48.206
A really empty house.

20:51.125 --> 20:52.919
(grunting)

20:52.961 --> 20:54.629
(panting)

20:54.671 --> 20:57.215
You know, when I was a kid,

20:57.256 --> 20:59.217
there was this place
down by the tracks.

20:59.258 --> 21:00.927
A real shithole gin joint.

21:00.969 --> 21:02.637
The place barely had a roof,

21:02.679 --> 21:04.597
-but they got some great
musicians to play there.
-Yeah?

21:04.639 --> 21:06.391
Louis Armstrong
stopped by one night.

21:06.432 --> 21:08.309
Blew the fucking roof
off the place.

21:08.351 --> 21:10.979
The owner, Mario--
he let me hang out there.

21:11.020 --> 21:13.356
Threw me a couple of bucks
if I ran errands,

21:13.398 --> 21:15.108
bought the guys cigarettes,

21:15.149 --> 21:17.568
hauled some beer crates
out of the cellar.

21:18.778 --> 21:20.780
I loved that place.

21:20.822 --> 21:23.241
(siren wailing in distance)

21:24.492 --> 21:26.327
Maybe it wasn't the comedy.

21:26.369 --> 21:28.079
What do you mean?

21:28.121 --> 21:31.499
Clearly, I'm not funny,
but maybe it was the club life,

21:31.541 --> 21:33.251
the club scene,
maybe that's what I loved.

21:33.292 --> 21:35.420
I have to say,
I always thought you were funny.

21:35.461 --> 21:37.046
-Archie.
-You always make me laugh.

21:37.088 --> 21:39.132
Your impression
of your Uncle Moe slays me.

21:39.173 --> 21:41.426
I'm talking professional funny.

21:41.467 --> 21:43.052
Midge funny.

21:43.094 --> 21:45.555
Oh. Well, yeah,
you're definitely not that.

21:46.806 --> 21:48.808
I think I'm gonna do it.

21:48.850 --> 21:51.811
I think I'm gonna open a club.

21:51.853 --> 21:53.855
(car horn honks)

21:59.819 --> 22:01.529
(grunting)

22:01.571 --> 22:03.489
(panting)

22:03.531 --> 22:06.492
I guess now we have
to pick up all those balls?

22:06.534 --> 22:08.286
Yup.

22:08.327 --> 22:10.413
Probably should have thought
about that before we started.

22:10.455 --> 22:13.624
So many things we should have
thought about before we started.

22:23.051 --> 22:25.094
♪ ♪

22:31.350 --> 22:36.189
Charles, I'd like to talk to you
in the secure room... now.

22:40.443 --> 22:42.403
(buzzer sounds)

22:42.445 --> 22:45.656
I'm very busy, Abe, so
we'll need to make this brief.

22:45.698 --> 22:49.035
I talked to my daughter Miriam
about your concerns,

22:49.077 --> 22:50.661
and I can assure you...

22:50.703 --> 22:52.288
(buzzer sounds)

22:52.330 --> 22:53.831
Abe, you remember
Martin Cummings.

22:53.873 --> 22:55.541
He's with our Government
Liaison Department.

22:55.583 --> 22:57.585
-Hello, Abe.
-Yes, hello, Martin.

22:57.627 --> 22:59.712
-But, Charles, we don't need...
-(buzzer sounds)

22:59.754 --> 23:03.049
Abe, you remember Bob Jackson,
head of our in-house counsel.

23:03.091 --> 23:04.592
Yes. Hello, Bob.

23:04.634 --> 23:06.844
But, Charles, what I want
to say doesn't require...

23:06.886 --> 23:08.471
(buzzer sounds)

23:08.513 --> 23:10.765
And, of course,
Devlin Mclaine, obviously.

23:10.807 --> 23:12.266
He's here as a witness.

23:12.308 --> 23:14.310
(buzzer sounds)

23:15.603 --> 23:17.605
They must have buzzed
the wrong room.

23:19.315 --> 23:21.526
We're done.

23:21.567 --> 23:24.278
Okay. As I was saying,

23:24.320 --> 23:26.739
I talked to Miriam,
and she told me...

23:26.781 --> 23:28.282
(clearing throats)

23:28.324 --> 23:30.326
(chairs squeaking on floor)

23:33.037 --> 23:36.249
She did not say anything

23:36.290 --> 23:39.377
about any project
we are working on here.

23:39.418 --> 23:41.170
She made a joke

23:41.212 --> 23:44.632
about the record I was playing
at home, and that is all.

23:44.674 --> 23:46.050
She's a comedian.

23:46.092 --> 23:48.136
They humiliate their families
onstage.

23:48.177 --> 23:50.012
That's their job.

23:50.054 --> 23:51.931
So, no harm was done.

23:51.973 --> 23:54.725
Okay?

23:54.767 --> 23:56.727
We don't see it that way, Abe.

23:56.769 --> 23:58.688
Clearly, she knew
you were working on something.

23:58.729 --> 24:01.232
-I'm always working
on something.
-At the very least,

24:01.274 --> 24:02.733
-you were extremely...
-Loose-lipped.

24:02.775 --> 24:04.443
Extremely loose-lipped
about the situation.

24:04.485 --> 24:06.529
-We don't like loose lips.
-They sink ships.

24:06.571 --> 24:08.239
I've heard the phrase.

24:08.281 --> 24:10.241
CHARLES: Why were you even
listening to this album at home?

24:10.283 --> 24:11.576
Don't you have access
to a bunker

24:11.617 --> 24:13.119
or a bomb shelter of some sort?

24:13.161 --> 24:14.871
You can't be serious.

24:14.912 --> 24:16.539
You played the album
in front of your daughter.

24:16.581 --> 24:18.708
You then confirmed to her
that you were indeed working

24:18.749 --> 24:20.585
on a Bell Labs
government project.

24:20.626 --> 24:22.253
That alone puts you
in breach of contract.

24:22.295 --> 24:24.005
So, not only are you
a security risk,

24:24.046 --> 24:25.381
your daughter is one as well.

24:25.423 --> 24:26.549
She might want
to retain a lawyer.

24:26.591 --> 24:28.467
-CHARLES: A good one.
-She's a comedian.

24:28.509 --> 24:29.886
And a girl.

24:29.927 --> 24:32.305
What kind of risk
could she possibly be?

24:32.346 --> 24:34.390
If I told you that,
then I would be a security risk.

24:34.432 --> 24:37.059
And if I listen to that,
then I would be a security risk.

24:37.101 --> 24:39.562
You came to me, remember?

24:39.604 --> 24:43.191
You came to Columbia
and-and begged me to come here

24:43.232 --> 24:44.775
and give you my expertise.

24:44.817 --> 24:46.110
And I did.

24:46.152 --> 24:48.279
And now you treat me
like a criminal?

24:48.321 --> 24:52.366
Well, I can take that expertise
back as fast as I gave it.

24:52.408 --> 24:53.784
Think about that.

24:53.826 --> 24:55.203
You signed away
your intellectual property

24:55.244 --> 24:56.662
when you signed your contract.

24:56.704 --> 24:58.164
We own your expertise.

24:58.206 --> 24:59.999
You can't own my expertise!

25:00.041 --> 25:01.167
It's mine!

25:01.209 --> 25:03.961
I think you should leave now.

25:09.884 --> 25:12.345
When I was a young man,

25:12.386 --> 25:15.348
I marched against people
like you.

